an></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My qualifications in various subjects are as follows:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Electrical:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">WJEC Course B (Credit)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C&amp;G 17</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Edition wiring Regulations (BS7671)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C&amp;G 2391 Inspection, testin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g and certification of electrical installations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C&amp;G 2400 Design, erection and verification of electrical installations (Credit)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C&amp;G 2399-1 Installation of small scale solar Photovoltaic </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Health and Safety:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NEBOSH Certificate in Occupational Health and Saf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ety (Distinction)</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NEBOSH Certificate in Construction Health and Safety (Distinction)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Others:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BTEC D32/33 Assessors award</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I am a Technical member of the Institution of Occupational Health and Safety (IOSH)</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In my humble opinion the public are being, and h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ave been for a number of years, mislead by the operators of the schemes run by people like NAPIT, ECA/NICEIC.  All claim to be the one that offers the best of this and that.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Farce: Electrical contractors are offered a ‘choice’ of what organisation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sign up to when in fact they have very little choice at all.  If they try and operate without membership to one or the other of these schemes they are branded as the ‘cowboy’ element by default. These schemes actively tell the public that their members are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> vetted etc and that the best way for the public to ensure that the electrician they hire is competent and qualified is to ensure that the electrician is registered with a scheme.  This is sheer and utter nonsense.  A person such as myself would be such a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘cowboy’ just because I fail to contribute to the coffers of such schemes when I hold as many, if not more qualifications than some the people carrying out assessments for the operators.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Most of the schemes do not insist that their membership is qualified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in Inspection, testing and certification of electrical installations. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> I propose that ALL electricians should hold these qualifications as a matter of course.  How else can they possibly certify that the electrical installation they have installed (a) co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mplies with the regulations (b) is safe to use if they don’t know how to test it?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I also propose that Qualified Supervisors should hold inspection and testing qualifications along with a current qualification in the wiring regulations (BS7671 as amended).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This should be the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">minimum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> standard with the design qualification as a preferred plus.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Electricians should be placed on a national registrar such as GAS Safe and be licensed to practice. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One has only to look in magazines such as Professional Electricia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n to see some of the work carried out by members of these schemes</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Speaking as a qualified electrician, Health and Safety Practitioner and Assessor if I were asked to make a risk assessment of the skill assessment process used by some, if not all, the sche</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mes it would not be good.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Electrical competence is a mix of skill and experience underpinned with sound knowledge and proven in the crucible of the examination room.   A passion for quality and safety must be the guide here.  People without such skills </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and qualifications should not be allowed to be near electrical installations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As for people being classed as competent of work on electrical installations when they are, at best, half trained, the least said the better (I refer to Part P compliance/compet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ence schemes and I will treat the people who thought up this cunning plan and training programs with the utter contempt they deserve) In my humble opinion and from and electrical and H&amp;S point of view this is a disaster in the making.  Carpenters, kitchen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fitters and plumbers working on electrical circuits with a few weeks training?  Good call!</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I never thought I would need to ask this of our government but please, please do not let the public down.  Act now.  Do not be the ones to let people get killed as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">killed they will be.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Please make a national registrar.  Licence skilled and qualified electricians (The J.I.B. use a grading scheme where the issue grade cards after first viewing certificates and this seems to be a good start to copy) </span></li></ol></div></body></html>